text: I've done A LOT of research on these events and I can tell you that this dramatization of the 96 Everest Disaster is going to be just about as close as you can get to actually having real footage of the actual events. They even went as far as reproducing the cloths these people were wearing. I know this because the pictures that do exist of the disaster show this. Aside from Jake Gyllenhaal not being blond like Scott Fischer was. Looks pretty realistic to me. I only hope it does justice to the people who lost their battle with mother nature that fateful 48 hours on the mountain,because some of them were true professionals and some of the best mountaineer ever to walk this planet.

text: Having just finished Into Thin Air, I'd find it hard for any dramatization of the '96 disaster to be able to do justice to what is described by Krakauer. I don't think you could replicate the confusion, sickness and extremity of what those climbers went through. I'm no mountaineer, but I have been in a total whiteout on a ski slope and nothing could ever capture just the simple effect of vertigo and disorientation I had there. Now add altitude, exhaustion, high wind, triple digit temperature deficits, and sheer drops to the mix. I'll stick to reading more books by the survivors. The pen is mightier than the IMAX.

text: This is the true story of two different expeditions in 1996 who attempt to scale Everest but encounter massive storms on the descent down the mountain.  Everest is a stunning looking film that you come away from , feeling totally exhausted. Because it is so realistic you do feel you are with the climbers at times. Sure , it's a stock disaster movie but because of the nature of the true story behind it , you feel more connected. The special affects are amazing and the performances from Jason Clarke and Keira Knightley are great too.  I watched this in 3D but ended up taking the glasses off because it was so annoyingly dark so i recommend watching it in 2D instead.  It's a staggering statistic that 1 in 4 people who attempt to get get to the summit of Everest , dies. Why do people do it? that question is asked in this film but apart from the stock answer of " Because it's there" it is never really answered . Perhaps there isn't one?  8 out of 10

text: What a gripping, thrilling tension filled adventure with a great cast doing some of their best acting job. This is 2015 version of Alive with characters finding themselves in difficult position and having to endure merceless nature that is coming for their lives. I thought it was a great tribute to Rob Hall and deceased people , it is a well directed film with mt. everest being a true star here. There are times when you actually feel like you are with them climbing that mountain, sound editing is phenomenal so are visual effects. I liked how subtle the movie was in educating audience, how it showed strenght of human will and horror of survival. There are some pacing issues and cliches slash corny dialogue, but It is a rewarding, mesmerizing experience and if you like survival stories go check it out. 4/5.

text: I loved the movie. Its the best mountaineering movie I have seen since "Touching the Void" or "Vertical Limit". I recommend seeing Everest on Imax for sure. It is an accurate dramatization of the 96 disaster down to many details found in "Into Thin Air". Mind you, it is a Hollywood movie, so the only thing that bothered me is all the CGI. However, it doesn't take away from the story, which is the reason anyone should see the film. For anyone that wants to really see what alpine climbing and mountaineering is about, see the movie "Meru". Everest is a nice touch, but Meru is the real deal with no acting or dramatization. Real mountain, real timelapses and actual footage from climbers that couldn't even pay someone to cart camera gear up the mountain with them.

text: This comments section is shit. I don't think hardly anyone realises the truth behind this film. I have just got back from watching the film, and this is a real story. Rob dies at the end of the film, in the same way, at the same height, on the same mountain, at the same time, as he did in real life. His body still lies just below the southern summit of Mount Everest. His wife and daughter are both real people, and his daughter really was named Sarah to honour his last request. The Texan climber, Beck Weather, is still alive today, and still lives with his wife Peach. He lost his nose, his left cheek and both of his hands just as he does in the film. Will all you dipshits in the comments please shut up and show some respect for everyone who has died on Everest. R.I.P Rob.

text: Any climbers answer a Q? Watched the film and when they get near the Hilary Step, they have to fix ropes themselves as the Sherpas hadn't. They fixed new rope over old leaving the latter in place and so the routes up these mountains appear a mass of old rope and their fixtures.  Why don't they cut away the recognisable old ropes at the start of the climbing season and let it drop away leaving a less complex, less confusing and a all-round tidier route? If the old ropes are left in-situ, what's to stop a befuddled climber using them?  I appreciate its a judgment call on who's to say what is old rope and what if someone is using it? In other words you can't cut away rope you don't own and don't know for sure if its getting used. Anone?
